Philippine Stocks: Ayala Land, Metrobank, Metro Pacific

-- B y   C e c i l i a   Y a p
-- 
2011-02-14T04:25:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-14/philippine-stocks-ayala-land-metro-pacific-investments.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 12 p.m. close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 47.58, or 1.3
percent, to 3,796.73, its steepest gain since Feb. 2.  Banks:  Metropolitan Bank & Trust  Co. (MBT PM) rose 2.4
percent to 58.15 pesos, leading gains by Philippine lenders
after the central bank raised limits on loans to individual
borrowers participating in the so-called Public-Private
Partnership aimed at boosting construction of toll roads,
railways and airports.    Banco De Oro Unibank Inc . (BDO PM), the nation’s largest
lender, advanced 1.8 percent to 47.90 pesos, climbing the most
since Dec. 23.    Ayala Land Inc . (ALI PM), the Southeast Asian nation’s
largest builder, rallied 4.3 percent to 14.60 pesos, its
steepest gain since Jan. 27. The company said capital spending
will increase to 32.6 billion pesos ($744 million) this year
from 20.1 billion pesos in 2010 to fund ongoing and new projects
and to expand its land bank.  Profit in 2010 rose 35 percent to a record 5.46 billion
pesos as revenue climbed 24 percent, Ayala Land said in a filing
to the Philippine Stock Exchange. Its parent,  Ayala Corp . (AC
PM), advanced 4.8 percent to 339.80 pesos.    Metro Pacific Investments Corp . (MPI PM), a holding company
with investments in water, power and infrastructure, gained 1.7
percent to 3.54 pesos, halting a two-day, 7.7 percent slump.
Deutsche Bank AG initiated coverage of the company with a 12-
month share-price estimate of 3.80 pesos and a “hold” rating.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Cecilia Yap in Manila at   cyap19@bloomberg.net 
